  "summary": "After finishing his dental appointment with Mr. Morley at 58 Charlotte Queen Street, Hercule Poirot leaves the clinic. In the waiting room, he observes a nervous young man and a well-dressed man named Mr. Brent. As Poirot exits the building, he encounters a middle-aged woman in shabby green clothing getting out of a taxi; he assists her by retrieving her handbag and a fallen shoe buckle.\n\nLater, while eating lunch, Poirot receives a phone call from Inspector Japp informing him that Mr. Morley has shot himself. Poirot returns to the clinic to find Japp and a photographer examining the body. Mr. Morley is lying by the fireplace with a small black hole below his right temple and a handgun near his extended right hand. Although the gun bears only Morley's fingerprints, Japp is suspicious because Morley was a healthy, successful man with no apparent motive for suicide. Additionally, the gunshot was not heard, potentially due to the street noise and the soundproofing of the doors.\n\nThe body was discovered around 1:30 by the doorman, Alfred Biggs, after a patient became impatient at 12:30. Japp notes discrepancies in the patient records: the bellhop identified a frustrated patient as Miss Hilti, but the appointment book lists her as Miss Corby. Furthermore, the last recorded buzzer press was at 12:05 to bring up a patient named Mr. Ambrosio of the Savoy Hotel. Upon hearing this, Poirot privately questions the accuracy of the page's information.",
